1 (4) "Endowment agreement" means a written agreement between a charitable organization and a
2 donor or a charitable trust and a donor regarding the contribution made by the donor and accepted by the
3 charitable organization or the charitable trust that may include donor-imposed restrictions or other conditions
4 governing the use of the contribution.
5 (5) (a) "Endowment fund" means an institutional fund or part of an institutional fund that, under the
6 terms of a gift instrument, is not wholly expendable by the institution on a current basis.
7 (b) The term does not include assets that an institution designates as an endowment fund for its
8 own use.
9 (6) "Gift instrument" means a record or records, including an institutional solicitation, under which
10 property is granted to, transferred to, or held by an institution as an institutional fund.
11 (7) "Legal representative" means the administrator or executor of a person's estate, a surviving
12 spouse if a court judgment has settled the accounts of the estate, or a person designated in an endowment
13 agreement, whether or not the person has been born at the time of the designation, to act in place of a party to
14 the agreement for all matters expressed in the agreement and all of the actions the agreement contemplates,
15 including without limitation interpreting, performing, and enforcing the agreement and defending its validity.
16 (8) "Property" means real property, personal property or money, cryptocurrency, stocks, bonds, or
17 any other asset or financial instrument.
18
19 NEW SECTION. Section 3. Protections afforded. (1) Except where specifically required or
20 authorized by federal or state law, a charitable organization that accepts a contribution pursuant to a written
21 donor-imposed restriction may not violate the terms of that restriction without potential penalty.
22 (2) If a charitable organization violates a donor-imposed restriction contained in an endowment
23 agreement, the donor or that person's legal representative, 90 days after notification to the charitable
24 organization, may file a complaint within 6 years after discovery for breach of the endowment agreement. The
25 complaint may be filed in a court of general jurisdiction in the county where a charitable organization named as
26 a party has its principal office or principal place of carrying out its charitable purpose or in a court of the United
27 States whose district includes the county. The complaint may be filed regardless of whether the agreement
28 expressly reserves a right to sue or enforce, and it may not seek a judgment awarding damages to the plaintiff.
